To replicate the provided image using LaTeX with TikZ and PGFPLOTS, you can use the following code. This code generates a plot with quantiles, a true distribution line, and a legend for sample sizes.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepgfplotslibrary{fillbetween}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    width=10cm,
    height=8cm,
    xlabel={$ \alpha $},
    ylabel={$ q_\alpha[X^*_k] $},
    xmin=0, xmax=1,
    ymin=-3, ymax=3,
    legend pos=north west,
    legend cell align={left},
    legend style={draw=black, fill=white, font=\small},
    legend entries={True Distribution, Sample Size: 250, Sample Size: 500, Sample Size: 1,000, Sample Size: 2,000, Sample Size: 4,000},
    cycle list name=color list
]

% True Distribution
\addplot [red, thick] coordinates {
    (0, -2.8) (0.1, -2) (0.2, -1.5) (0.3, -1) (0.4, -0.5) 
    (0.5, 0) (0.6, 0.5) (0.7, 1) (0.8, 1.5) (0.9, 2) (1, 2.8)
};

% Simulated Distributions
\foreach \n/\color in {250/blue!20, 500/blue!40, 1000/blue!60, 2000/blue!80, 4000/blue} {
    % Mean line
    \addplot [\color, thick] coordinates {
        (0, -2.5) (0.1, -1.8) (0.2, -1.3) (0.3, -0.8) (0.4, -0.3) 
        (0.5, 0.2) (0.6, 0.7) (0.7, 1.2) (0.8, 1.7) (0.9, 2.2) (1, 2.5)
    };
    % 5th percentile
    \addplot [\color, opacity=0.5] coordinates {
        (0, -3) (0.1, -2.5) (0.2, -2) (0.3, -1.5) (0.4, -1) 
        (0.5, -0.5) (0.6, 0) (0.7, 0.5) (0.8, 1) (0.9, 1.5) (1, 2)
    };
    % 95th percentile
    \addplot [\color, opacity=0.5] coordinates {
        (0, -2) (0.1, -1.1) (0.2, -0.6) (0.3, -0.1) (0.4, 0.4) 
        (0.5, 0.9) (0.6, 1.4) (0.7, 1.9) (0.8, 2.4) (0.9, 2.9) (1, 3)
    };
}

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Key Features:
- **True Distribution**: The red line.
- **Simulated Distributions**: Different shades of blue lines, representing different sample sizes.
- **Legend**: Identifies the lines corresponding to each sample size.

